Let $G$ be an abelian group. A solution $(G, r)$ to the Yang--Baxter equation is called an \index{affine solution}{\it affine solution} if $r$ has the form
\begin{equation} \label{aff}
r(x,y) = \big(ax + by+z,~ cx + dy+t \big)
\end{equation}
for some $a, b, c, d \in \End(G)$ and $t, z \in G$.

\label{prop affine solution condition}
Let $G$ be an abelian group and $r : G \times G \to G \times G$ a map of the form \eqref{aff}. Then $(G, r)$ is an affine solution to the Yang--Baxter equation  if and only if the conditions \eqref{liner solution non-degen}-\eqref{leq3} and 
\begin{equation} \label{affine solution condition}
cdz+dt = 0,\quad az+bat=0 \quad \textrm{and}\quad (c+d-ad-1)z + (da+1-a-b)t=0
\end{equation}
hold.

